<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-935-234  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 935 234.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  Dec 4 1989 v6 n48 p13(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Comdisco to support network, adds DEC hot site in Toronto.andO;(Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Patch, Kimberly.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services Inc. (services).andO;Topic:     Disaster RecoveryPower SupplyComputer ServicesNetworks.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Comdisco To Support Network, Adds DEC Hot Site in TorontoandM;ROSEMONT, Ill.andP;  -- Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services (CDRS) has announcedthat over the next 15 months it will add extensive network support to itsdisaster recovery service.andM;&quot;The world of business recovery is changing.andP;  Hot-site customers are suddenlyfocusing as much on network solutions as on hardware,&quot; said Richard Zane,president of CDRS-North America.andM;The company has also announced that it has opened a fourth DEC hot site basedon a VAX 8700, in Toronto, and has added a VAX 6440 to its Chicago hot site.andM;The CDRS Network will consist of a dedicated T1 and T3 network connectingComdisco's four hot sites and a simulated trading floor in New York.andO;Networking services gateways will provide access to many long-distance andlocal carriers.andM;To increase redundancy and minimize single points of failure, the networkwill have access to copper-wire, fiber-optic, microwave, and satellitecommunications.andM;&quot;It provides transparent geographical access to whatever combination ofcapabilities [the user] needs,&quot; Zane said.andP;  &quot;Regardless of where the DEC orIBM [power] is, and regardless of geographical location, they'll [gain]access.andP;  It's an integration of IBM, DEC, Tandem, voice backup, and anythingelse we have,&quot; he said.andM;Also, &quot;we're in better control,&quot; Zane added.andP;  &quot;The routing capability of CDRS[will be] controlled by the customer and us as opposed to the carrier, as itis today.&quot;andM;The plan also calls for an emphasis on business recovery facilities inComdisco's Atlanta and Cypress, Calif., facilities that will add workstationsand a greater member of applications to the basic computational power of hotsites.andM;&quot;There's more dependency on specific applications,&quot; Zane added.andP;  &quot;[Customersare] looking for business recovery and the capacity to back up not only theirdata processing, but the users as well.&quot;andM;For additional information, Comdisco Disaster Recovery Services Inc. can becontacted at 611 N. River Road, Rosemont, IL 60018, (312) 698-3000.andO;</TEXT></DOC>